Focusable Elements - jQuery UI Compatibility Table

The following tables show the differences between what browsers consider focusable and what jQuery UI identifies.

Note that touch devices (without a physical keyboard) only show elements as tabbable (keyboard focusable), that can be navigated to through the on-screen keyboard (or "virtual keyboard").

Footnotes

  • The DOM Element Interface is missing the focus method.
  • The focus event is not emitted upon the element becoming the active element (document.activeElement).
  • The :focus CSS pseudo class is not set on the element when it is the active element (document.activeElement).
  • The element becomes the active element (document.activeElement) when an element of contentDocument or the shadowRoot has focus.

  • Note 2

    The <html> element itself is not considered focusable, but some browsers may give it focus when focus is passed from browser UI to the document.

  • Note 3

    The <body> element itself is not considered focusable, but it is has focus (i.e. is document.activeElement) if no other element has focus.

  • Note 4

    HTML5 does not specify that the <form> element knows the disabled attribute.

  • Note 5

    should not be focusable as per disabled elements. Blink 453847, Webkit 141086

  • Note 6

    The activation behavior of the <label> element is not defined beyond »… should match the platform's label behavior.«

  • Note 7

    Internet Explorer redirects focus from <label> to the referenced form control element upon mouse click, but not on script focus via element.focus().

  • Note 8

    The CSS property user-modify was proposed and dropped from CSS UI Level 3 and has thus not become a standard yet.

  • Note 9

    The value is invalid according to rules for parsing integers required by HTML5 tabindex

  • Note 10

    tabindex="" is parsed to the value -32768. Trident 1072965

  • Note 11

    The value's trailing spaces are considered invalid according to rules for parsing integers required by HTML5 tabindex

  • Note 12

    The value's trailing non-numeric characters are considered invalid according to rules for parsing integers required by HTML5 tabindex

  • Note 13

    The <map>'s <area>s are inert (not focusable) as long as the image is still loading.

  • Note 14

    If an <area> element doesn't have an href attribute, it's not a link (and should therefore not be interactive).

  • Note 15

    Some browsers will not make an image map focusable, if it is associated with an <img> that does have a proper image loaded.

  • Note 16

    <audio> is considered interactive content only with the <code>controls</code> attribute present

  • Note 17

    <video> is considered interactive content only with the <code>controls</code> attribute present

  • Note 18

    Shadow DOM is currently only "properly" supported in Blink based browsers (Chrome, Opera). Firefox exposes the (considerably buggy) development state behind flags.

    See Can I Use.

  • Note 19

    Regardless of its own focusable state, an element hosting a Shadow DOM can become the activeElement if an element inside the ShadowRoot has focus. See Shadow DOM - Active Element

  • Note 20

    The activeElement is scoped within the Shadow DOM, meaning the master documet does not know which shadowed content currently has focus. To indicate that a shadowed element has focus, the element hosting the shadowed content is made the activeElement regardless of its ability to receive focus otherwise.

  • Note 21

    Technically the content of an iframe can be accessible to script.

  • Note 23

    There is no API to interact with the content document of an <embed> element

  • Note 25

    <object> with visibility:hidden should not be focusable - Blink 586191

  • Note 26

    Technically the content of an <object> element can be accessible to script.

  • Note 28

    The behavior of the <embed> element depends on the content type and browser plugin.

  • Note 30

    The <video> element should be used for embedding video content instead of <embed> element. The HTML5 <video> element is supported virtually everywhere.

  • Note 31

    It is highly recommended to embed <svg> directly into the document or use the <object> element instead.

  • Note 32

    The behavior of the <object> element depends on the content it presents. The most common content types used with <object> are SVG and SWF.

  • Note 33

    This element is actually tabbable (keyboard focusable).

    But when tabbing to it, the <kbd>Tab</kbd> behavior for the entire document breaks, as focus remains stuck on the browser UI.

    This might be related to Trident 1109008.

  • Note 34

    SVG 1.1 does not specify much in respect to accessibility. SVG 2 will bring the tabindex attribute. SVG Tiny 1.2 knows the focusable attribute.

  • Note 35

    By registering a focus event listener the element becomes focusable. Blink 445798, WebKit 140024.

    This is undetectable because elements don't provide a list of their registered event handlers.

  • Note 37

    IE9 and IE10 do not support the hidden attribute.

  • Note 38

    The hidden attribute itself has no effect on whether an element is focusable or not. It's the CSS style disaply: none that is set by the hidden attribute that counts.

  • Note 39

    The <details> element is specified in HTML 5.1, but not implemented everywhere.

  • Note 40

    This element should be keyboard focusable (tabbable), but is currently only focusable because of WebKit 151767

  • Note 41

    This element should not be focusable (tabbable), but is currently only focusable because of WebKit 151767

  • Note 42

    Internet Explorer turns <div> and <span> elements focusable when they're scrollable, but does not do the same for other sectioning or block-level elements

  • Note 43

    The ismap attribute makes the <img> focusable (in addition to the parent <a>)

  • Note 44

    There is no indication that the focusability of an element can be inherited by its children, let alone triggered by flexbox layout.

  • Note 46

    Firefox may hide elements from the document's tabbing sequence if they're enclosed by two images referencing the same image map - Gecko 1116126.

  • Note 47

    This test is not about an element's focusable state, but about potentially content that's potentially hidden from the tabbing sequence.

  • Note 48

    Firefox transforms <keygen> to <select _moz-type="-mozilla-keygen"> while parsing HTML.

  • Note 49

    The <keygen> element is poorly supported, practically never used and has seen intent to deprecate

  • Note 51

    Keyboard focusable (tabbable) content in nested browsing contexts (<iframe>, <object>, <element>) is demoted to script and mouse focusable if the browsing context container has tabindex="-1".

  • Note 52

    The focusable state of descendant elements of an <svg> element are not affected by tabindex="-1" on the <svg> element, contrary to the behavior of browsing contexts (<iframe>, <object>, <element>).

  • Note 53

    The focusable state of content elements in Shadow DOM are not affected by tabindex="-1" on the shadow host, contrary to the behavior of browsing contexts (<iframe>, <object>, <element>).

  • Note 54

    Focus is redirected to the labeled control.

  • Note 55

    Focus is redirected to the nested labeled control.

  • Note 56

    Focus is redirected to the the next keyboard focusable (tabbable) element after the <legend> in DOM order (not in order of the document's tab sequence). Note that this does not necessarily have to be a descendant of the same <fieldset> element.

  • Note 57

    Focus is redirected to the the first focusable form control element (<input>, <select>, <textarea>, <button>) of the <fieldset> the <legend> is the child of.

  • Note 58

    Focus is redirected to the the first <area> element of the referenced image map.

  • Note 59

    The <iframe>'s document manages its own focus. Any time the <iframe> or its content has focus, the master document's activeElement points to the <iframe>.

    Note that <iframe>s are only accessible to script when they share the same origin.

  • Note 60

    Browser plugins running the <embed> can manage their own focus. Any time the <embed> or its content has focus, the master document's activeElement points to the <embed>.

    Note that the content of <embed> elements is not accessible to scripting from the outside, but from within the <embed>'s document JavaScript can interact with window.parent.

  • Note 61

    The <object>'s document manages its own focus. Any time the <object> or its content has focus, the master document's activeElement points to the <object>.

    Note that <object>s are only accessible to script via element.contentWindow when they share the same origin.

  • Note 62

    Whenever an element within a ShadowRoot has focus, the element hosting the ShadowRoot is considered the activeElement of the document, as per the active element adjustment algorithm.

    Firefox' Shadow DOM implementation still has a few problems: Gecko 1117535, Gecko 1117544, Gecko 1117552.
